@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "About this Site";
}

<div class="container bg-light rounded p-4 mb-4">
    <h2>@ViewData["Title"]</h2>
</div>

<div class="container">
    <h4>History</h4>
    <p>
        In June of 2016, the Pathfinder team, a subset of the ExpressRoute PM team, started building two
        physical customer repro labs at Equinix in Seattle, WA (SE3) and Ashburn, VA (DC2). Creating,
        maintaining, and removing individual tenant environments, ensuring they were isolated, secure,
        and usable was a labor and time intensive, manual effort.
    </p>
    <p>
        To ease the burden of multiple configurations (Juniper, Cisco, PowerShell, Hyper-V, etc) a
        spreadsheet was created. Called the "Configuration Generator" it was a macro-based (vba) Excel
        spreadsheet.
    </p>
    <p>
        The spreadsheet was used to generate the Azure PowerShell and on-premises network device config
        and VM config needed to run multiple concurrent customer environments, called "Tenants". This
        worked well for a few years, until a more robust conversation was needed between Azure and the
        configuration generator. Things like dynamic IP addresses, or ER Direct Port S-Tags which are
        generated in Azure when the environments are created, were needed in the on-premises configuration.
        Given these addresses and tags are dynamically assigned at creation, a multi-step back and forth
        was needed to utilize this information. To avoid building REST handlers in VBA in Excel, it was
        decided to move this tool to a web based application where interacting with online services can
        happen natively from the Configuration Generation tool.
    </p>
    <p>
        This site is the web evolution of that spreadsheet.
    </p>

    <h4>Site Construction</h4>
    <p>
        This site is built on ASP.NET Core (.NET 10) using Razor views with Bootstrap styling,
        Entity Framework Core for data access, and is hosted as an Azure App Service in West US 2.
        It uses an Azure SQL Server backend for data storage with Entra ID (Azure AD) authentication
        via Easy Auth and Managed Identity — no passwords or connection strings with secrets.
        Authorization is provided by a Users table in the database with per-user, manually assigned
        permission levels (AuthLevels 0-15).
    </p>

    <h4>Roadmap</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Full tenant CRUD and configuration generation</li>
        <li>IP address management and assignment</li>
        <li>Workshop registration and management</li>
        <li>Automated Azure deployment orchestration</li>
        <li>On-prem automation of VM creation and network device configuration</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Known Issues</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>None, Jon don't write no bugs! (that make it into production)</li>
    </ul>
</div>

